## Artifact paths (one folder per part / project)

Every part — single OR multi-part project — lives in its own folder
under `artifacts/`. This isolates designs from each other, gives the
user a clear unit to share or print, and lets the README sit next to
the files it documents.

**Single-part layout** (default for a one-part request):

```
artifacts/<part-name>/
├── <part-name>.py             ← source of truth (git-tracked)
├── <part-name>.session.json   ← turn state (gitignored)
├── <part-name>.step           ← on export only (gitignored)
├── <part-name>.stl            ← on export only (gitignored)
└── README.md                  ← on export only — minimal BOM
```

**Multi-part project layout** (when Phase 0 multi-part detection fires):

```
artifacts/<project-name>/
├── shared.py                  ← all shared params (git-tracked)
├── project.json               ← parts list + interfaces (git-tracked)
├── <part-A>.py                ← per-part script (git-tracked)
├── <part-A>.session.json      ← per-part turn state (gitignored)
├── <part-B>.py
├── <part-B>.session.json
├── (on export) <part-A>.step, <part-A>.stl, <part-B>.step, <part-B>.stl
├── (on export) assembly.step, assembly.stl    ← combined preview
└── (on export) README.md                       ← full BOM with print order, fasteners, assembly
```

### Path-resolution on every first-turn invocation

When the user starts a /cad-coder session, walk this lookup in order:

1. Compute the part-name (kebab-case from the description).
2. Check `artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.session.json` (new convention)
   → if found, **resume that session**.
3. Check `artifacts/<part-name>.session.json` (legacy flat layout from
   pre-folder versions) → if found, resume in place AND note in the
   report: "Resuming legacy flat-layout part. Your next export will
   move this into `artifacts/<part-name>/` automatically." Do the move
   atomically on the next export turn.
4. Check `artifacts/<part-name>/project.json` → if found, **resume the
   multi-part project**.
5. None found → fresh session, create `artifacts/<part-name>/` and
   sketch into it (Phase 1A single-part) OR, if Phase 0 multi-part
   detection fires, proceed to Phase 1B (project bootstrap).

If the same part-name has both a flat-layout file AND a folder (rare,
indicates an aborted migration), prefer the folder and surface a
warning: "Found both `artifacts/<part-name>.py` and
`artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.py`. Using the folder version; the
flat-layout file is stale. Delete it or move it manually if it has
useful history."

