### First-turn bootstrap report

After Phase 1B builds the skeleton and validates all parts:

```
Project: fpv-drone-case  (3 parts, casual mode)

Parts sketched:
  - bottom-shell   80 × 40 × 15 mm  |  vol 28.4 cm³  |  41 faces
  - top-shell      80 × 40 × 15 mm  |  vol 18.2 cm³  |  22 faces
  - camera-mount   18 × 12 ×  8 mm  |  vol  1.1 cm³  |  14 faces

Interfaces:
  - main-seam     bottom ↔ top via 4× M3 (Ø2.9 boss / Ø3.4 clear), 1.5×1.0 gasket groove
  - camera-dovetail bottom ↔ camera-mount via Ø12×18 dovetail, +0.2mm slip

Shared params live in artifacts/fpv-drone-case/shared.py. Edits to
shared params re-validate every part. Edits to a single part touch
just that part's script.

Focused on: bottom-shell.

Observations:
  - GASKET_D 1.0mm on a 0.4mm-nozzle print needs at least 2 layers to
    not look terrible — set layer ≤ 0.2mm or bump to 1.2mm groove.
  - The camera-dovetail at +0.2mm slip will be loose for a sticky cam
    on PLA; tighten to +0.1mm if you're not using rubber bands.

What's next?
  → "tighten cam dovetail to 0.1mm" — apply observation 2
  → "switch to top-shell" — work on a different part
  → "add a vent slot to top-shell" — feature add on a non-focused part
  → "drop the assembly" when ready to print all of them
```


The chat loop runs the script in **validate-only** mode every turn.
That means: cadquery builds the solid in memory, prints geometry
stats (bbox, volume, faces), and **does not write STEP or STL**.
Iterating on width / hole size / fillet through 10 turns produces
zero junk files in `artifacts/`. The user only gets files when they
explicitly ask (Phase 3).

```bash
mkdir -p artifacts
CAD_PY=$(./bin/cad-python 2>/dev/null || echo python3)
$CAD_PY artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.py
```

`./bin/cad-python` (resolver in this repo — see Environment check
below) finds whichever Python actually has cadquery installed:
the local `.cad-venv` first, then `python3.12`/`python3.11`/
`python3.10` / `python3` from PATH. If none have cadquery, it exits
non-zero so you fall back to plain `python3` and the import error
is visible.

**Multi-part projects:** if the edit touches `shared.py`, re-validate
EVERY part in the project, not just the focused one. Walk
`project.json["parts"]` and run each script. Diff against the
per-part `last_geometry` snapshots and surface every part whose
geometry changed (see Phase 3's "Cascade validation" section for the
report format). If the edit touched only a part's own script, just
re-validate that one part.

The `__main__` block prints one JSON line with `"exported": false`
on a validate-only run. Parse it and update
`session.json["last_geometry"]`. Hard checks before reporting success:

| Check | Action if failed |
|-------|------------------|
| `volume_mm3` > 0 | Boolean op produced empty solid — debug, do not ship |
| `bbox_mm[0..2]` matches the LENGTH/WIDTH/HEIGHT params (±0.01mm) | Script bug — debug |
| (export turns only) `<name>.step` exists, > 1KB | Export silently failed — re-run |

If any hard check fails, fix the script and re-run silently. Do not
report success until the geometry sanity-checks pass (and on export
turns, the file lands).

### Stress check (engineered mode only)

If `session.mode == "engineered"` AND `session.requirements.load_case`
is set AND `session.engineered_constraints` has a filament σ_y, run a
closed-form stress estimate via `cad-coder/stress.py` every validate
turn. This catches "the spec says FoS 5.0 but the actual geometry
delivers FoS 2.1" *before* the user prints.

Step 1 — pick the geometry class from the part shape. Heuristics:

| Shape signal | Geometry class | Reasoning |
|--------------|----------------|-----------|
| Long-thin part, mount holes at one end, load at the other | `cantilever` | Bracket holding a mass at its tip |
| Two mount sets across a span, load in the middle | `beam` | Simply-supported beam |
| Flat-ish (length × width >> thickness), holes spread, distributed load | `plate` | Mounting plate under center pull |
| Screw tightening against a thin wall under axial pull | `pull_through` | M-screw extracting plastic cone |
| Boss under axial squeeze (screw clamp, stack-up) | `boss` | Compressive axial load |

If you can't pick one cleanly, pick the **most conservative** one (the
one with the highest stress estimate for the given dimensions). Note
the choice in the report so the user can correct: "Assuming cantilever
— if the load is actually distributed across the long edge instead,
say 'use beam geometry' and I'll re-estimate."

Step 2 — extract the dimensions from the part's params:

```bash
$CAD_PY cad-coder/stress.py cantilever \
  --L <effective_length>  \
  --b <width>             \
  --h <thickness>         \
  --F <load_n>            \
  --sigma_y <sigma_y_mpa> \
  --layer_factor <1.0 in-plane or 0.5 cross-layer FDM>
```

For cantilever-like parts, `effective_length` is the distance from
the fixed mount to the load point — NOT the overall part length.
A 60mm bracket with mount holes at one end and a load at the far
end has effective length ≈ 60mm; a 60mm bracket where the load is
at the centre is effective length ≈ 30mm.

`load_n` comes from `session.requirements.load_case` — convert mass
to force (kg × 9.81). If the load is cyclic, multiply by 2× for fatigue
(rule of thumb — peak amplitude beats RMS for plastic fatigue).

Step 3 — read the JSON output:

```json
{
  "geometry": "cantilever_beam_tip_load",
  "max_stress_mpa": 28.12,
  "location": "root of cantilever (top/bottom fibre at fixed end)",
  "fos": 1.6,
  "verdict": "marginal — likely to deform under load, may not break",
  "inputs": {...},
  "sigma_y_mpa": 45.0, "layer_factor": 1.0
}
```

Surface in the engineered-mode report as ONE line under the
`Engineering:` line, with the verdict in plain language:

```
Engineering: FoS 5.0 spec · σ_y 45 MPa (PETG, in-plane) · WALL ≥ 2.4mm
Stress check: 28 MPa at the root (cantilever model, ~30% accurate)
              actual FoS 1.6 — marginal, will deform under sustained load.
              Add a 4mm fillet at the wall or bump WALL to 6mm to reach FoS 3.0.
```

When `actual_fos < spec_fos`, ALSO surface in `Observations:` with a
proposed fix:

```
Observations:
  - Stress check says actual FoS = 1.6, you specced 5.0. Either the
    geometry needs help (thicker wall, supporting rib, larger fillet
    at the load point) or the load estimate was conservative. Want me
    to bump WALL to the value that meets FoS 5.0? (calculated: 6.6mm)
```

**Honesty rules:**
- Always cite the formula name in the report ("cantilever model",
  "plate model").
- Always show ±30% in the first turn the stress check runs ("rule-of-
  thumb, ~30% accurate — for production parts, use real FEA").
- Never round FoS to "looks fine" when it's < 1.5 — surface the number.
- If geometry doesn't fit any of the 5 formulas (complex topology,
  multiple load paths, contact mechanics), say so: "I can't model this
  shape with the closed-form formulas; skipping stress check this turn.
  /qa-print after printing is the next-best validation."

Cache the latest stress result in `session.json["last_stress"]` so the
report can show the delta when a parameter edit changes it:

```json
"last_stress": {
  "geometry": "cantilever_beam_tip_load",
  "max_stress_mpa": 28.12,
  "fos_actual": 1.6,
  "fos_spec": 5.0,
  "computed_at_turn": 4
}
```

### Environment check (first turn only)

```bash
CAD_PY=$(./bin/cad-python 2>/dev/null) && $CAD_PY -c "import cadquery; print(cadquery.__version__)"
```

The resolver checks, in order: `.cad-venv/bin/python`,
`.venv/bin/python`, then `python3.12`, `python3.11`, `python3.10`,
`python3` from PATH. First one that successfully imports `cadquery`
wins; if none do, the resolver exits non-zero and you should offer
to install:

```bash
# Recommended: isolated venv on a cadquery-compatible Python
uv venv --python 3.12 .cad-venv
uv pip install --python .cad-venv/bin/python cadquery
```

cadquery doesn't yet support Python 3.13 / 3.14 reliably — the OCP
wheel only ships for 3.10-3.12. Don't try to install on a newer
interpreter; create a 3.12 venv instead. Do not silently `sudo`
anything.

## Phase 3: Report + Edit Loop (every turn after the first)

After every successful run, output exactly this shape — short, scannable,
ending in an open question. Pick the shape that matches `session.mode`.

### How to generate the `Observations:` block

Aim for 1-2 observations per turn (sometimes 3 if engineered mode and
real trade-offs landed). NEVER make them up — they should reference an
actual condition of the current part, the current edit, or the session
history. Sources to scan, in priority order:

1. **Printability margins** — any feature near a print floor (wall
   close to 4×nozzle, fillet < nozzle width, overhang close to 45°,
   bridge close to 10mm, hole-inset close to fastener-head radius).
   These are concrete and quantifiable; lead with these.
2. **Engineered constraint margins** (engineered mode only) — FoS
   sitting at exactly the threshold with no margin, fit within
   0.05mm of a different class, layer-direction factor matching the
   most-stressed axis. Note the headroom (or lack of it).
3. **Pattern in recent edits** — three turns of WALL shrinking → "are
   you trying to hit a specific size?"; two turns of adding cuts → "do
   you want me to track the remaining wall thickness anywhere?".
4. **Filament-aware alternatives** — same geometry on a stiffer or
   tougher filament with a real-world delta ("PA-CF: -30% mass, +$2").
5. **Cost-aware nudges** — if quantity > 5, mention per-unit material
   cost when relevant. If print time crosses an hour, mention it.
6. **Comfort / ergonomics** — handheld parts without chamfers, sharp
   external corners, small grippable surfaces.

NEVER list more than 3. If nothing observable, write `Observations:
(none — clean turn)` instead of inventing filler. A silent observation
is worse than a redundant one, but a fake one is worse than silence.

### How to generate state-aware `What's next?` suggestions

Three rules:
1. **Reference what's in `session.json` right now** — features that
   exist, params that were just edited, observations that haven't been
   addressed. Not a generic menu.
2. **The first suggestion should apply observation #1**, the second
   should apply observation #2, the third should propose something the
   user hasn't said yet but you'd expect them to want next (a next-
   logical-feature add, a print-readiness check, an export prompt).
3. **Always include the export option as the LAST line**: `→ "drop the
   stl" when you're ready to print`. Unless we're already post-export,
   in which case offer `→ "re-export" for a fresh STL with the latest
   edits` instead.

**Casual-mode validate-only report** (the default — most turns):

```
Sketched: mounting-bracket  (turn 4)
Assumed: FDM print, M3 clearance holes, 4 corners, no fillets.
Geometry: 60 × 40 × 4 mm  |  Volume 7.10 cm³  |  22 faces
Features: body, mount_holes

Observations:
  - HOLE_INSET is 5mm — that's tight for an M3 head + washer (you'd
    have 1mm of clearance to the edge). Want me to bump to 7mm?
  - 4mm thickness will print in ~25 minutes but feels thin in hand —
    if this is going to be handled often, 6mm is sturdier with little
    cost. (Skip if it's bolted out of sight.)

What's next?
  → "bump HOLE_INSET to 7" — apply observation 1
  → "make it 6mm thick" — apply observation 2
  → "add a chamfer to the top edge" — comfort if handheld
  → "drop the stl" when you're ready to print
```

**Casual-mode export-turn report** (only on export turns — see Export
signals below):

```
Built: artifacts/mounting-bracket.step + .stl  (exported on turn 7)
Geometry: 60 × 40 × 4 mm  |  Volume 7.10 cm³  |  22 faces
Features: body, mount_holes

After you print it: run /qa-print to check the fit. Don't need calipers
— a ruler is fine.
```

**Engineered-mode validate-only report** (default; adds engineering +
print orientation, never omit them in engineered mode):

```
Sketched: motor-bracket  (turn 2, engineered)
Requirements: 5kg cyclic, bolts to frame via 4× M3, FDM PETG, 0.4mm nozzle, 5 units.
Engineering: FoS 5.0 cyclic · σ_y 45 MPa in-plane (PETG, cited) · layer factor 1.0 · WALL ≥ 2.4mm · boss slip Ø8.2 · holes Ø3.4.
Print: Y-up, largest face on bed · est. print time 1h45m @ 0.2mm layer · ~22g PETG.
Geometry: 80 × 60 × 12 mm  |  Volume 28.43 cm³  |  38 faces  |  Mass ≈ 35.8 g @ 1.26 g/cm³
Features: body, boss, mount_holes, load_fillets, first_layer_chamfer

Observations:
  - Current WALL = 2.4mm is FoS = 5.0 exactly — no margin if your load
    estimate was optimistic. PA-CF at the same wall gives FoS = 10
    for ~$2 more in filament; switch?
  - The boss Ø8.2 is 0.05mm under the no-play threshold for PETG —
    will slide on, may have ~0.1° wobble. If this is camera-grade,
    tighten to locating fit (Ø8.15).
  - Print time 1h45m at 0.2mm layer; bumping to 0.28mm cuts it to ~1h
    with negligible strength cost in-plane.

What's next?
  → "switch to PA-CF" — apply observation 1
  → "tighten boss to locating fit" — apply observation 2
  → "use 0.28mm layer" — note in session, surfaces in /qa-print later
  → "drop the stl" when you're ready to print
```

**Engineered-mode export-turn report** — same as casual export-turn,
plus the Engineering / Print lines preserved above the Built line.

Mass = volume × filament density when filament is known. Print time
estimate is a rule of thumb (volume / typical-flow-rate) — surface as
"est." so the user knows it's pre-slicer. Both are the cheapest sanity
checks on whether the part makes physical sense.

**On export turns ONLY, add the /qa-print hint** at the bottom of
the report:

```
After you print it: run /qa-print to check the fit. Don't need calipers
— a ruler is fine.
```

Do NOT add this hint on validate-only turns — nothing has been
exported, so there's nothing to print yet. The hint matters when a
fresh STEP/STL just dropped.

### Export signals (what flips the run to export mode)

When the user signals they want files, run the script with `--export`
and emit the export-turn report. Trigger phrases include (not
exhaustive — read intent, not exact strings):

| Signal | What the user said |
|--------|---------------------|
| "ready to print" | "okay print it", "let's print this", "ready for the printer" |
| "drop / give the file" | "drop the stl", "give me the stl", "export it", "save the files", "ship the stl" |
| "lock it in" | "lock this in", "ship this version", "this is the one" |
| Verbose pause | "I think we're done", "looks good, I'll print it" — confirm once: "Exporting now — STEP + STL?" → on yes, run with `--export` |

On every **single-part export turn**, do exactly four things:
1. Run the script with `--export` to drop
   `artifacts/<part>/<part>.step` and `artifacts/<part>/<part>.stl`.
2. Update `session.json["last_exported_at"]` with the ISO-8601 UTC
   timestamp, and `session.json["last_exported_turn"]` with the turn
   number.
3. Write the `cad-built` downstream artifact (see "Downstream artifact"
   below). Validate-only turns do NOT write this artifact — it would
   spam `~/.gstack/projects/` with intermediate steps that aren't
   really builds.
4. Write / update `artifacts/<part>/README.md` (see "BOM README on
   export" section below) so the folder is shareable and the user has
   a one-glance summary of what they just exported.

On a **multi-part project export** ("drop the assembly" / "export
everything"), do:
1. Run every part's script with `--export` — drops one `.step` + `.stl`
   per part in `artifacts/<project>/`.
2. Build a `cq.Assembly()` that positions every part using the
   shared params (e.g., top-shell stacked above bottom-shell at
   `Z = BODY_HEIGHT/2`, camera-mount slotted into the dovetail at
   the recorded offset). Export `artifacts/<project>/assembly.step`
   and `assembly.stl` for previewing the whole thing in one viewer.
3. Update `project.json["last_exported_all_at"]` and each part's
   `session.json["last_exported_at"]`.
4. Write ONE `cad-built` artifact per part, plus one combined
   "project-built" entry that lists the parts and the assembly file.
5. Write / update `artifacts/<project>/README.md` as a **full BOM**
   (parts list with print times + mass, recommended print order,
   per-part print settings, fastener BOM, assembly steps, interface
   summary, regenerate command). See "BOM README on export" below
   for the exact format.

Per-part export inside a project ("just drop the camera-mount") behaves
like single-part: that part exports, others stay validate-only, no
combined assembly written.

If the user keeps editing after an export, return to validate-only
mode automatically — they're refining post-export, which usually
means the previous STL is now stale. Surface it once when you detect
this: "STL is now 2 turns stale — say 'export' when you want a fresh
one."

### Handling the next instruction

Map every user instruction to one of these edit types. Pick the
narrowest one that fits.

| Instruction shape | Edit type | Mechanics |
|-------------------|-----------|-----------|
| "make X 50mm" / "switch to M4" / "thicker walls" | **Parameter edit** | Edit one `PARAM = value` line in the script. Update `session.json["params"]`. Validate-only run. |
| "add a cable slot" / "pocket the bottom" / "boss on top" | **Feature add** | Add one new named-feature block between the existing ones and `result = ...`. Update `session.json["features"]` and reassign `result` to the new feature. Validate-only run. |
| "remove the fillet" / "drop the mounting holes" | **Feature remove** | Delete the named-feature block. Reassign `result` to the previous feature. Update `session.json["features"]`. Validate-only run. |
| "go back two turns" / "undo" | **Session replay** | Read `session.json["history"]`, regenerate the script from the params at turn N. Append a new history entry; do not delete old ones. Validate-only run. |
| "save this as a variant" / "branch" | **Snapshot** | `cp -R artifacts/<part>/ artifacts/<part>-<tag>/` (whole folder), then update the new folder's session.json with `parent: <original>`. Implies export so the snapshot has STEP+STL+README of that variant. |
| "drop the stl" / "ready to print" / "export" / "ship it" | **Export** | Run script with `--export`. Drops `artifacts/<part>/<part>.step` and `.stl`. Write cad-built artifact. Update `last_exported_at`. Write/update `artifacts/<part>/README.md`. |

**Additional edit types — multi-part projects only** (when `artifacts/<project>/project.json` exists):

| Instruction shape | Edit type | Mechanics |
|-------------------|-----------|-----------|
| "make the case 100mm long" / "tighten all fits to slip" / any edit referencing a `shared.py` name | **Shared param edit** | Edit `shared.py`, then re-validate ALL parts. Surface which parts changed (geometry delta). Update `project.json["shared_params"]`. |
| "the dovetail should be Ø15 not Ø12" / "loosen the main-seam clearance" | **Interface change** | Edit the interface's shared params in `shared.py`, re-validate both sides of the interface, surface the impact on each side. Update `project.json["interfaces"][N]` if the constraint description changed. |
| "switch to top-shell" / "show me the camera-mount" / "focus on X" | **Part focus** | Update `project.json["focused_part"]` to the named part. Subsequent instructions apply to that part by default. Re-render the report for the new focus. |
| "add a vent slot to top-shell" / part-specific feature add when not focused | **Cross-part feature add** | Edit the named part's script (not the focused one), validate just that part, briefly switch focus or note "edit applied to top-shell, still focused on bottom-shell". |
| "add a new part: lens-cap" / "split the bottom into front and back" | **Add part / split part** | Create a new `.py` + `.session.json` in the project dir, add to `project.json["parts"]`, sketch with shared params + propose new shared-param names if needed. Reorganise the parts list. |
| "drop the assembly" / "export everything" / "ship all parts" | **Project export** | Run every part's script with `--export`. Build a `cq.Assembly()` that positions each part and export `artifacts/<project>/assembly.step` + `assembly.stl` (one combined file for previewing the whole thing; individual STLs are what get printed). Write cad-built artifact for each part + one for the assembly. |
| "drop just the camera-mount" | **Single-part export from project** | Run just that part's script with `--export`. Other parts stay validate-only. |

### Cascade validation for shared param edits (multi-part only)

When a shared param changes, the chat loop must re-validate every
part that imports it. Order of operations:

1. Edit `shared.py` (one-line change in the right interface group).
2. Re-run every part script in validate-only mode.
3. Diff the geometry (`bbox_mm`, `volume_mm3`) per part against
   `project.json["parts"][N].last_geometry`.
4. Surface every affected part in the report, even if the focused
   part wasn't one of them:

```
Edited: SCREW_PATTERN_X 60 → 70  (shared)
Affected parts:
  - bottom-shell:  bbox 80×40×15 → 80×40×15 (unchanged) | boss positions moved
  - top-shell:     bbox 80×40×15 → 80×40×15 (unchanged) | hole positions moved
  - camera-mount:  not affected (doesn't use SCREW_PATTERN_X)

Observation:
  - SCREW_PATTERN_X 70 with BODY_LENGTH 80 leaves only 5mm of edge
    distance on the screw bosses. That's tight for an M3 head — at 70
    you'll lose some strength on impact. Bump BODY_LENGTH to 86 to
    keep ≥10mm edge, or drop SCREW_PATTERN_X to 64?
```

If a re-validation fails (boolean op produced empty solid, etc.) on
ANY part after a shared edit, do NOT silently leave the project in a
broken state. Surface which part broke and offer to revert.

**Hard rule:** Parameter edits and feature adds/removes must NEVER
rewrite the geometry pipeline as a whole. If you find yourself
reformatting the entire `Workplane(...)` chain to satisfy a one-line
ask, that's a signal the original sketch wasn't truly feature-named —
refactor *that*, then make the edit.

### Engineered-mode guard on every parameter edit

If `session.mode == "engineered"`, **before applying any parameter
edit**, check it against `session.engineered_constraints`:

| Constraint | Check | Action on violation |
|------------|-------|---------------------|
| `wall_min_mm` | New wall ≥ FoS × load / (σ_y × layer_factor) AND ≥ nozzle minimum | Refuse silent edit; surface "WALL 2.4 → 1.6 would drop FoS from 5.0 to 3.3 under the recorded load. Confirm downshift, or pick a different value." |
| `*_fit` | Edited hole/boss diameter still gives the recorded fit (clearance/slip/press) for the filament | Re-compute the empirical diameter for the new nominal size; warn if user gave a value that breaks the fit |
| `fillet_min_mm` | Load-bearing fillets ≥ max(0.5× new wall, nozzle width) | Auto-bump fillet, or surface "WALL increased — load fillet should grow to N mm." |
| `print_z_axis` | Load axis still in-plane after orientation change | Surface "Flipping Z-up makes the recorded load cross-layer (factor 0.5). FoS would drop from 5.0 to 2.5. Re-spec the wall or revert." |

### Printability guards (every turn, both modes)

Print-friendliness checks that run after the script generates and
before the report. These apply to casual mode too — a part that won't
print is useless regardless of whether it's load-rated.

| Check | Threshold | Action |
|-------|-----------|--------|
| Unsupported bridge length | > 10mm (PLA/PETG), > 5mm (PC/Nylon) | Surface "10mm+ unsupported bridge on `<feature>` — will sag. Add support, split the part, or redesign." |
| Overhang angle | > 45° from vertical | Surface "65° overhang on `<feature>` — needs supports or a 45° chamfer." |
| Min wall < nozzle minimum | < 4× nozzle width for load, < 2× for cosmetic | Surface "WALL 0.6mm is below 4× nozzle (1.6mm) — will print but will be weak." |
| Internal corner < nozzle radius | < nozzle / 2 | Surface "Internal corner 0.1mm — slicer can't resolve at 0.4mm nozzle. Add a fillet ≥ 0.2mm." |
| Min printable feature | < 0.4mm XY, < 0.2mm Z | Surface "Detail too small for 0.4mm nozzle / 0.2mm layer — will be lost." |

Surface every guard hit in the next report under an `Engineering note:`
or `Printability note:` line. Do not silently override the user — they
are allowed to break a constraint, but they must do it on purpose.
Record any acknowledged downshift in `session.requirements` (e.g.,
`"prototype_override": "FoS 5.0 → 3.0 on turn 3"`).

A guard hit is **not** a hard validation failure (Phase 2). The script
still runs; the geometry is still valid; we are flagging an
engineering-intent or printability regression, not a code bug.

### Append to history every turn

```json
{"turn": 2, "instruction": "make it 50mm wide", "diff": "WIDTH 40 → 50"}
```

The `diff` field is a one-line plain-English summary, not a unified
diff. It's what `session.json` shows the user when they ask "what did
we change last?"

### Live preview (opt-in, browser-based)

cad-coder ships with a Three.js viewer in `cad-coder/ui/` that watches
a `.glb` file and reloads via server-sent events when the file changes.
Use it when the user wants to **see** the part while iterating — turns
the chat loop from "imagine the bracket from the bbox numbers" into
"click-and-spin the actual model after every edit."

**Trigger phrases:** "show me the preview", "open the viewer", "let me
see it", "spin it up", "live preview", "open it in 3D".

**Mechanics:**

1. On the preview-launch turn, run the script ONCE with `--preview` to
   generate the initial GLB next to the `.py`:
   ```bash
   $CAD_PY artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.py --preview
   ```
   This writes `artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.glb` without writing
   STEP or STL. Cheap (~ same cost as a validate run).

2. Launch the UI server in the background, pointed at the GLB:
   ```bash
   _ROOT=$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel 2>/dev/null || pwd)
   _MODEL_ABS="$_ROOT/artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.glb"
   _PORT=${CAD_CODER_PORT:-8765}
   bun "$_ROOT/cad-coder/ui/server.ts" \
     --model "$_MODEL_ABS" \
     --project-root "$_ROOT" \
     --port "$_PORT" &
   echo "Preview: http://127.0.0.1:$_PORT"
   ```
   Tell the user the URL. They open it in a browser; it stays open
   across turns.

3. On EVERY subsequent validate turn while preview is active, set
   `CAD_PREVIEW=1` when running the script so the GLB regenerates:
   ```bash
   CAD_PREVIEW=1 $CAD_PY artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.py
   ```
   The script's `__main__` block writes the GLB. The UI's file-watcher
   detects the change and reloads the canvas through SSE — the user
   sees the new geometry without refreshing the browser.

4. Track preview state in `session.json["preview"]`:
   ```json
   "preview": {
     "active": true,
     "port": 8765,
     "url": "http://127.0.0.1:8765",
     "started_at": "2026-05-16T13:20:00Z",
     "last_glb_at": "2026-05-16T13:24:18Z"
   }
   ```
   When `preview.active` is true, prepend every Phase 3 report with:
   ```
   Live preview: http://127.0.0.1:8765 (model auto-reloads each turn)
   ```

5. The user can stop the preview with "close the preview" / "stop the
   viewer" — kill the bun process, set `preview.active = false`, and
   stop adding `CAD_PREVIEW=1` to validate runs.

**Preview vs export:**

| Mode | What runs | What writes | Cost per turn |
|------|-----------|-------------|---------------|
| Validate (default) | script | JSON stats only | ~ms |
| Validate with preview | script + GLB export | JSON + GLB | ~50-200ms |
| Export (signal turn) | script + STEP + STL + GLB | all three | ~500ms |

GLB is the right format for previewing because it's the web-native 3D
format and Three.js loads it natively. STEP and STL are still the
shippable formats — GLB is preview-only.

**For multi-part projects:** the preview shows the **assembly** GLB, not
a single part. The assembly GLB regenerates on every validate turn
(against any part) when preview is active, so changes to any part are
visible in the combined viewer. The watcher in `cad-coder/examples/
watch-cadquery.ts` is the reference for re-running CAD scripts on file
change — useful if you want a watch-mode dev loop outside of /cad-coder.

**Examples ship with the skill:** `cad-coder/examples/cadquery-whistle.py`
is a worked-example part you can preview to confirm the UI is working
before sketching your own. `cad-coder/README.md` documents the UI
contract for skill authors who want to point it at a different exporter.

### Downstream artifact: write `cad-built` ONLY on export turns

When (and only when) an export turn drops a fresh STEP+STL, write a
project-scoped artifact so `/retro`, `/qa-print`, and any other
downstream skill can pick up what was built. Validate-only turns do
NOT write this artifact — the parameter tweak history lives in
`session.json` locally; only actual exports earn a project-scoped
"build" record.

```bash
{{SLUG_SETUP}}
BRANCH=$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo HEAD)
USER_SLUG=$(git config user.email 2>/dev/null | sed 's/@.*//' | tr -c 'a-zA-Z0-9' '-' | sed 's/--*/-/g; s/^-//; s/-$//')
TS=$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H-%M-%S)
mkdir -p ~/.gstack/projects/$SLUG
OUT=~/.gstack/projects/$SLUG/${USER_SLUG}-${BRANCH}-cad-built-${TS}.md
```

Artifact format (Markdown — both human-readable and easy to parse):

```markdown
# cad-coder build · <part-name> · turn N

- **Mode:** casual | engineered
- **Part name:** <kebab-case>
- **Script:** artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.py
- **Session:** artifacts/<part-name>/<part-name>.session.json
- **Built at:** <ISO-8601 UTC>
- **Triggered by:** <one-line user instruction this turn>

## Geometry
- Bounding box: L × W × H mm
- Volume: N.NN cm³
- Faces: N
- Mass (if filament known): N.N g @ ρ g/cm³

## Engineering (engineered mode only)
- FoS: N.N (static | cyclic)
- Filament σ_y: N MPa in-plane / N MPa cross-layer (source)
- Layer-direction factor: 1.0 | 0.5
- Print orientation: <Z-up axis>
- Fits applied: <slip/clearance/press summary>

## Features
- body, mount_holes, cable_slot, load_fillets, ...

## Notes (only if guard hits this turn)
- Engineering: <FoS / fit / fillet violations and resolutions>
- Printability: <bridge / overhang / wall / corner violations>

## Upstream
- Brief: ~/.gstack/projects/<slug>/<...>-design-<datetime>.md   (if picked up)
- None — sketched from inline description
```

One artifact per turn (don't overwrite). `/retro` globs the whole set
to summarise what was built this week. The naming convention matches
`-test-outcome-` and `-test-plan-` so the gstack project root has a
single coherent shape.

### BOM README on export

Every export turn writes `README.md` next to the STL — single-part gets
a minimal version, multi-part gets a full bill of materials. The file
is overwritten each export, NOT appended (it's a snapshot of "what's
in this folder right now", not a log).

**Single-part `artifacts/<part>/README.md`:**

```markdown
# <part-name>

<One-line description from session.requirements or original ask>

## Print

- **STL:** `<part-name>.stl`
- **Suggested orientation:** Y-up, largest face on bed
- **Suggested supports:** OFF (or "TREE supports on the overhang at ...")
- **Suggested brim:** 5mm  (or "None" if PLA)
- **Estimated print time:** ~1h45m at 0.2mm layer
- **Estimated material:** ~22g PETG

## Slicer profile

- Bambu Studio: Generic PETG, 0.2mm layer, 20% infill, supports OFF, 5mm brim
- PrusaSlicer: 0.20mm SPEED, PETG, 20% infill, supports None, brim 5mm
- OrcaSlicer: 0.20mm Standard, Generic PETG, 20% infill, supports None
- Cura: 0.2mm normal, PETG, 20% infill, supports None, brim 5mm

(Pick one line for the user's slicer; default to Bambu if unknown.)

## Parameters

Edit `<part-name>.py` and re-run to regenerate. The `.py` is the
source of truth; STEP / STL regenerate from it.

| Param | Value | Note |
|-------|-------|------|
| LENGTH | 60 mm | overall length |
| WIDTH | 40 mm | overall width |
| HEIGHT | 4 mm | thickness |
| HOLE_DIAMETER | 3.4 mm | M3 + 0.4mm clearance |
| HOLE_INSET | 5 mm | from edge |
| FILLET_RADIUS | 1 mm | corner softening |

## Regenerate

```bash
cd artifacts/<part-name>
python <part-name>.py <part-name>.step --export
```

## After printing

Run `/qa-print` to verify the fit. Bring a ruler — no calipers needed.
```

**Multi-part `artifacts/<project>/README.md` (full BOM):**

```markdown
# <project-name>

<One-line project description>

Multi-part project. N parts that assemble together. Print them all,
follow the assembly steps below.

## Parts list

| # | Part | File | Volume | Mass (<filament>) | Est. print time |
|---|------|------|--------|-------------------|-----------------|
| 1 | bottom-shell | `bottom-shell.stl` | 28.4 cm³ | ~36g | 1h45m |
| 2 | top-shell | `top-shell.stl` | 18.2 cm³ | ~23g | 1h10m |
| 3 | camera-mount | `camera-mount.stl` | 1.1 cm³ | ~1.4g | 12m |

**Total:** 47.7 cm³, ~60g <filament>, ~3h overall print time.

## Recommended print order

1. **camera-mount first** (small, fast — also a print-quality canary)
2. **bottom-shell** (medium — verify dovetail mates before printing top)
3. **top-shell** (largest, longest — print last after everything validated)

## Print settings per part

| Part | Z-up | Supports | Brim | Notes |
|------|------|----------|------|-------|
| bottom-shell | Y | OFF | 5mm | <reason> |
| top-shell | Y | OFF | 5mm | same |
| camera-mount | Z | TREE on dovetail face | None | overhang > 45° |

Slicer-recommended: **Generic <filament>, 0.2mm layer, 20% infill**
(bump infill on load-bearing parts where engineered-mode flagged it).

## Fasteners (BOM)

| Fastener | Quantity | Use |
|----------|----------|-----|
| M3 × 12mm button head screw | 4 | main seam (bottom ↔ top) |
| (Optional) M3 nyloc nut | 4 | anti-vibration on main seam |

Total: 4× M3×12 BHCS.

## Assembly steps

1. **Test interface fits first** before committing to all-parts print:
   - Dovetail fit between bottom-shell and camera-mount — slip fit, slight
     resistance. Too tight: file 0.1mm; too loose: re-print with
     CAM_DOVETAIL_CLEAR = 0.15mm.
2. <part-specific assembly step in plain language>
3. <next step>
4. **Final screw-down**: 4× M3×12 BHCS, snug not crushing.

## Interfaces (for re-iteration)

- **main-seam** (bottom-shell ↔ top-shell): SCREW_PATTERN_*, GASKET_*
- **camera-dovetail** (bottom-shell ↔ camera-mount): CAM_DOVETAIL_*

Shared params: `shared.py` — edit there to propagate to every
affected part.

## Regenerate

```bash
cd artifacts/<project-name>
# Single part:
python bottom-shell.py bottom-shell.step --export
# Or rebuild the whole project from gstack:
/cad-coder rebuild <project-name>
```

## After printing

Run `/qa-print` per part to verify fits. /qa-print can also do the
full assembly check: "do they all fit together?"
```

### Rules for the README generator

1. **Source of truth** is the part's session.json (single-part) or
   project.json + each part's session.json (multi-part). Don't invent
   data — only surface what's recorded.
2. **Filament density** for mass: PLA 1.24, PETG 1.27, ABS 1.04,
   ASA 1.07, PC 1.20, Nylon 1.14, PA-CF 1.16, TPU 1.21 g/cm³.
3. **Print-time estimate** uses ~15 cm³/hour at 0.2mm layer / 0.4mm
   nozzle / ~100 mm/s. Surface as "~Nh Nm" — clearly an estimate.
4. **Slicer profile lines** — show the one matching the user's
   recorded printer if known, otherwise default to Bambu Studio.
5. **Assembly steps for multi-part** — generate per-interface based
   on `project.json["interfaces"]`. Each interface becomes one step.
   Plain language, no jargon — assume a non-engineer is following.
6. **Snapshot, not log.** Re-export overwrites README.md fully. The
   per-turn history lives in `session.json["history"]` and the
   cad-built artifacts, not in README.

---

{{LEARNINGS_LOG}}

## Additional Rules (cad-coder specific)

1. **Never fabricate dimensions silently.** When you guess a default,
   put it in `session.json["assumptions"]` and surface it in the
   report. Wrong physical parts waste material and time.
2. **No GUI assumptions.** Do not require `cq-editor` or Jupyter. The
   skill must work headless via `python3 script.py`.
3. **Track the source, ignore the build artifacts.** Committed to git
   (per part folder): the `.py` files, `shared.py` (multi-part),
   `project.json` (multi-part), and `README.md` (the BOM). Gitignored:
   `.step`, `.stl`, `.session.json` (regenerate fresh from the `.py`).
   The patterns are in `.gitignore`:
   ```
   artifacts/**/*.step
   artifacts/**/*.stl
   artifacts/**/*.glb
   artifacts/**/*.session.json
   artifacts/qa-print/
   ```
   The `**` glob handles any depth — single-part folder, multi-part
   project folder, snapshot variants. Do NOT gitignore `artifacts/` as
   a whole; that would drop the source `.py` files too.
4. **STEP first, STL second.** STEP preserves the CAD model
   (parametric re-import works). STL is triangulated dead-end — fine
   for printing, useless for editing.
5. **One part per script, projects for assemblies.** If the request is
   a single object (bracket, knob, clip), one `.py` in `artifacts/` is
   right. If it's an assembly (case, enclosure, mount-with-snap-on-
   accessory, anything with mating parts), use a multi-part **project**:
   `artifacts/<project>/` with `shared.py` + `project.json` + per-part
   `.py` files that all `from shared import *`. See Phase 1B. Never
   cram multiple parts into one `.py` (you lose per-part edit + per-
   part print) and never duplicate shared dimensions across sibling
   scripts (drift bug waiting to happen).
6. **Mention cost when relevant.** If the user is making 50 of these
   in titanium and the volume is 100cm³, surface that. Geometry
   decisions have material-cost consequences.
